Diagnosis of adult male ( Figs 17A–D , 18G–M , 19 ):
In all studied morphotypes, the male characters are more ‘generalized’ compared with female characters, i.e. (1) body less deep, lacking a hump; (2) if antenna I is very long in the female (
B. coregoni gibbera
), it is comparatively shorter in the male; by contrast, if the female antenna I is short (
B. crassicornis
), it is comparatively longer in the male; (3) if mucro is very long in the female (
B. longispina
), it is comparatively shorter in the male; by contrast, if mucro is short (
B. coregoni kessleri
) in the female, it is longer in males. In
B. crassicornis
the female has no mucro, but there is a small mucro in its male. As a result, males of all morphotypes are remarkably more similar in general appearance than are the females.
